---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import DocsShell from '~/components/widgets/DocsShell.astro';

const metadata = {
  title: 'Quickstart — Aitroop Docs',
};
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <DocsShell current="quickstart">
    <h1>Quickstart</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Build your first App in about five minutes. We'll go from an empty chat to a parameterized,
      shareable workflow that your whole team can run.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>What you'll need.</strong> An Aitroop account (sign up at <a href="https://app.aitroop.net">app.aitroop.net</a>),
      and one realistic task you'd like the agent to do — something repetitive enough that turning it into an App actually pays off.
      Example tasks: weekly engineering report, daily lead enrichment, monthly AR aging review.
    </div>

    <h2>1. Open a chat</h2>
    <p>
      From the dashboard, click <strong>New chat</strong>. This drops you into a Chat with the agent — the
      exploration surface. Anything you type here runs in a fresh sandbox, with the agent able to use any
      Skills you've installed and any Connects you've authorized.
    </p>
    <p>
      Treat the chat as a draft. You're not committing to anything yet. Try one phrasing of the task,
      look at the result, refine, try again. This is where you find what actually works.
    </p>

    <h2>2. Ask the agent to do the real job</h2>
    <p>
      Be concrete. The more specific the first message, the better the first result. A useful template:
    </p>
    <div class="code-block">
<span style="color:var(--aw-color-text-muted)"># Task</span><br/>
Pull all commits from <span style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">shop-frontend</span> between <span style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">2026-05-01</span> and <span style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">2026-05-07</span>.<br/>
<br/>
<span style="color:var(--aw-color-text-muted)"># Output</span><br/>
A markdown daily report, grouped by author. Include PR titles. Skip merge commits.<br/>
<br/>
<span style="color:var(--aw-color-text-muted)"># Constraints</span><br/>
- Language: Chinese<br/>
- Keep it under one page per day
    </div>
    <p>
      The agent will use the <code>github</code> Connect (assuming you've authorized it) and the
      <code>git-log</code> skill, then write the report as a markdown <strong>Artifact</strong>.
      Preview it in the right pane.
    </p>

    <h2>3. Iterate until it's right</h2>
    <p>
      Most of the value of Chat mode is here. Reply to the agent the same way you'd reply to a teammate:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>"Skip dependabot commits."</li>
      <li>"Group by repository, not author."</li>
      <li>"Add a section at the top with the top 3 themes of the week."</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Every reply produces a new Artifact. Once one of them is the version you want to keep running every week,
      you're ready to save.
    </p>

    <h2>4. Click "Save as App"</h2>
    <p>
      Above the chat, there's a <strong>Save as App</strong> button. Clicking it does two things:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        The agent re-reads the conversation and identifies the parts that should become <strong>parameters</strong> —
        the repository name, the date range, the output language. Anything that could reasonably change next time
        is offered as an input.
      </li>
      <li>
        The agent freezes the goal of the conversation into a reusable <strong>Stage</strong>. The exploration
        is over; the workflow is now stable.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      You'll see a draft App with a form (inputs) and a description (the stage's goal). Review the inputs:
      remove anything that should be hard-coded, add anything the agent missed.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Inputs in your draft App come from the chat.</strong> If the agent picked <code>shop-frontend</code> as a fixed
      string instead of a <code>repo</code> input, just edit the App and add it. You don't have to get the chat
      perfect — you just have to be able to recognize "this part should change next time" when you see the draft.
    </div>

    <h2>5. Name it, save it, run it</h2>
    <p>
      Give the App a name (<code>Weekly engineering report</code>), an optional icon, and a visibility setting
      (Private, Team, or Public within your workspace). Click <strong>Save</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The App now lives in your library. Click <strong>Run</strong>, fill in the form, and the agent
      executes the saved workflow — same result, every time, with whatever inputs you give it.
    </p>

    <h2>6. (Optional) Put it on a schedule</h2>
    <p>
      From the App page, click <strong>Schedules → New schedule</strong>. Pick a cron expression
      (<code>0 9 * * MON</code> for Mondays at 9 AM), choose where the Artifact should be delivered
      (email, Slack, Drive, a webhook), and save.
    </p>
    <p>
      That's it. Every Monday morning, your inbox has last week's engineering report. You wrote one chat;
      the platform turned it into a system.
    </p>

    <h2>What you just built</h2>
    <p>
      An App with one Stage, a handful of AppInputs, and a markdown Artifact — running on a weekly cron.
      That's the entire loop. Multi-stage Apps, more Skills, more Connects, more output formats are all
      variations on the same pattern.
    </p>

    <div class="next-up">
      <span class="label">Next</span>
      <a href="/docs/concepts">Core concepts — Chat, App, AppInput, Stage, Artifact</a>
    </div>
  </DocsShell>
</Layout>
